   829→
   830→## 8. Permission / Tool Approval Flow
   831→
   832→### Three-Layer Decision Pipeline
   833→
   834→The CLI evaluates permissions through three layers before sending a `can_use_tool` over the wire:
   835→
   836→```
   837→Tool Use Request
   838→  │
   839→  ├─► Layer 1: PreToolUse Hooks (local shell scripts)
   840→  │     ├─ allow → tool executes
   841→  │     ├─ deny → tool blocked
   842→  │     └─ ask → fall through
   843→  │
   844→  ├─► Layer 2: Local Rule Evaluation (R5z)
   845→  │     ├─ Check deny rules → if match → DENIED
   846→  │     ├─ Check ask rules → if match → behavior="ask"
   847→  │     ├─ Check mode:
   848→  │     │   bypassPermissions → ALLOWED (never reaches wire)
   849→  │     │   dontAsk → DENIED (never reaches wire)
   850→  │     ├─ Check allow rules (incl. --allowedTools) → ALLOWED
   851→  │     └─ Default → behavior="ask"
   852→  │
   853→  └─► Layer 3: Remote Prompt (WebSocket)
   854→        └─ Sends control_request { subtype: "can_use_tool", ... }
   855→           ├─ Response: { behavior: "allow", updatedInput: {...} } → EXECUTE
   856→           └─ Response: { behavior: "deny", message: "..." } → BLOCKED
   857→```
   858→
   859→### `updatedInput` — Modifying Tool Arguments
   860→
   861→When responding with `{ behavior: "allow" }`, you **must** include `updatedInput`. This replaces the tool's input entirely. You can:
   862→- Pass through unchanged: `updatedInput: original_input`
   863→- Sanitize commands: Change `rm -rf /` to `echo "blocked"`
   864→- Modify paths: Restrict file access
   865→
   866→### `updatedPermissions` — Learning Rules
   867→
   868→Return `updatedPermissions` to save rules for the session or settings:
   869→
   870→```typescript
   871→type PermissionUpdate =
   872→  | { type: "addRules", rules: { toolName: string, ruleContent?: string }[], behavior: "allow"|"deny"|"ask", destination: PermissionDestination }
   873→  | { type: "replaceRules", rules: [...], behavior: "...", destination: "..." }
   874→  | { type: "removeRules", rules: [...], behavior: "...", destination: "..." }
   875→  | { type: "setMode", mode: PermissionMode, destination: PermissionDestination }
   876→  | { type: "addDirectories", directories: string[], destination: PermissionDestination }
   877→  | { type: "removeDirectories", directories: string[], destination: PermissionDestination }
   878→
   879→type PermissionDestination = "userSettings" | "projectSettings" | "localSettings" | "session" | "cliArg";
   880→```
   881→
   882→**Example — Auto-approve future git commands:**
   883→```json
   884→{
   885→  "behavior": "allow",
   886→  "updatedInput": { "command": "git status" },
   887→  "updatedPermissions": [
   888→    {
   889→      "type": "addRules",
   890→      "rules": [{ "toolName": "Bash", "ruleContent": "git:*" }],
   891→      "behavior": "allow",
   892→      "destination": "session"
   893→    }
   894→  ]
   895→}
   896→```
   897→
   898→### Timeout Behavior
   899→
   900→- If the server never responds to `can_use_tool`, the CLI blocks indefinitely
   901→- The CLI can send `control_cancel_request` to cancel its own pending request
   902→- On transport close, all pending requests are rejected with `"Tool permission stream closed before response received"`
   903→
